King, Rowling, and Shakespeare
By 0, 9/29/2003

AROLD BLOOM'S condemnation of Stephen King is a glaring example
of what is wrong with academia when it takes itself too seriously
and looks down on the rest of us. William Faulkner once said of
Ernest Hemingway, ''He has never been known to use a word that
might send a reader to the dictionary.'' To which Heminway
replied, ''Poor Faulkner. Does he really think big emotions come
from big words?'' Bloom scolds King and J.K. Rowling for being
popular writers who don't necessarily use big words. Perhaps he
has forgotten another writer, popular for his time, who wrote
audience-pleasing material. His name was William Shakespeare. I
can attest to the ability of King, Rowling, and Shakespeare to
craft a story.

I can't say the same for Don DeLillo, whose ''White Noise'' was
likely as self-absorbed as it was critically acclaimed by Bloom.

JOSHUA LERNER

