(quote)
The Boston Globe
The loss of truly great literature
By 0, 10/1/2003

UNLIKE MOST READERS who have responded to Harold Bloom's Stephen
King ''bashing'' by bashing Bloom, I heartily agree with him.
Stephen King's fiction is cheap, as King himself readily admits.
It's pulp, basically, and he knows it. At best, reading it is a
guilty pleasure for mature, more demanding readers. To compare
him to Shakespeare based on his popularity, as one letter writer
did (Sept. 29), shows the kind of muddled thinking that rightly
horrifies Bloom. What Shakespeare shows us is that great writing
can be popular and accessible, not that all writing that is
popular and accessible is great.

Great writing transforms the reader and his world. It opens the
mind to new possibilities. But it's not sheer escapism. It
demands (to paraphrase the poet Rilke) that you change your life.

What Bloom mourns is not only the lack of truly inspiring,
transformative work these days but the hostility its very
existence garners. The unwillingness or inability to distinguish
between truly great books and merely mediocre ones is not just a
matter of mental hygiene; it is vital to the care of the soul.

D.A. D'AREZZO
(unquote)

