(quote)
The Boston Globe
Stephen King is a wonderful writer
By 0, 9/29/2003

AS A 20-YEAR-OLD woman attending the University of Massachusetts
in Amherst who has been an avid reader since elementary school, I
was greatly insulted by Harold Bloom's Sept. 24 op-ed article
''Dumbing down American readers.'' I was insulted by his bashing
of Stephen King as an author, claiming that he is an immensely
inadequate writer on a sentence-by-sentence,
paragraph-by-paragraph, book-by-book basis. I began my life as a
reader as an unabashed fantasy/sci-fi junkie and now adoringly
read the classics: Rudyard Kipling, Charles Dickens, Edgar Allan
Poe, etc. Robert Louis Stevenson is, in fact, my favorite author.

However, I also find Stephen King to be a wonderful writer who
brings the reader into his text and never lets him/her go. Would
Bloom prefer a person never read at all? Would he prefer a
student to read about Romeo lamenting over the fact that Rosaline
would not have sex with him (''Romeo and Juliet,'' William
Shakespeare), or how alcoholism destroys families (''The
Shining,'' Steven King)?

And let us not forget that in his own century, Shakespeare was
considered entertainment only for the uneducated drudges of
society.

I also would like to extend my congratulations to Stephen King
for achieving the National Book Foundation's annual award for
distinguished contribution. He has earned it.

JACQUELIN C. CALDWELL
(unquote)

