Getting closer to the mother of all nightingale poems now.
Here are excerpts from two of George Gascgoine's poems
from 1576, both of which begin with something about
nightingales.

George Gascgoine &quot;The Steel Glass&quot;, published 1576.
Here Gascgoine portrays the nightingale as
having a cheerful song, which relieves the depressing
thoughts of the poet, much like Keats' nightingale.
First stanza:

The Nightingale, (whose happy noble heart,
No dole can daunt, nor feareful force affright,
Whose cheerfull voice, doth comfort saddest wights,
When she her self, hath little cause to sing.
Whom lovers love, because she plains their griefs,
She wraies their woes, and yet relieves their pain,
Whom worthy minds, always esteemed much,
And gravest years, have not disdaind her notes:
(Only that king proud Tereus by his name
With murdring knife, did carve her pleasant tongue,
To cover so, his owne foul filthy fault)
This worthy bird, hath taught my weary Muse,
To sing a song, in spight of their despite,
Which workemy woe, without cause or crime,
And make my back, a ladder for their feet,
By slandrous steps, and stairs of tickle talk,
To climb the throne, wherein my selfe should sit.
O Phylomene, then help me now to chant:
And if dead beasts, or living birds have ghosts,
Which can conceive the cause of carefull moan,
When wrong triumphs, and right is overtrod,
Then help me now, O bird of gentle blood,
In barren verse, to tell a fruitfull tale,
A tale (I mean) which may content the minds
of learned men, and grave Philosophers.

Gascgoine Philomel 1576
In this poem the nightingale has a sad song. Keats
wonders whether he is awake or dreaming in his poem,
while Gascgoine here actually falls asleep and dreams.

IN sweet April, the messenger to May,
When honey drops, do melt in golden showers,
When every bird, records her lovers lay,
And western winds, do foster forth our flowers,
Late in an even, I walked out alone,
To hear the descant of the Nightingale,
And as I stood, I heard her make great moan,
Lamenting much, And thus she told her tale.

These thriftless birds (quoth she) which spend the day,
Are costly kept, and finely fed alway
With dainty food, whereof they feed their fill.
But I which spend, the dark and dreadful night,
In watch and ward, when those birds take their rest,
Forpine my self, that Lovers might delight,
To heare the notes, which break out of my brest.
I leade a life, to please the Lovers mind,
(And though god wot, my food be light of charge,
Yet seely soul, that can no favor find)
I beg my bread, and seek for seeds at large.
The Throstle she, which makes the wood to ring
With shreeching loud, that loathsome is to hear,
Is costly kept, in cage: (O wondrous thing
The Mavis eke, whose notes are nothing clear,
Now in good sooth (quoth she) sometimes I weep
To see Tom Tyttimouse, so much set by.
The Finch, which singeth never a note but peep,
Is fed as well, nay better far than I.
The Lennet and the Lark, they sing aloft,
And compted are, as Lordes in high degree.
The Brandlet saith, for singing sweet and soft,
(In her conceit) there is none such as she.

Canara birds, come in to bear the bell,
And Goldfinches, do hope to get the goal:
The tattling Awbe doth please some fancy well,
And some like best, the birde as Black as coal.
And yet could I, if so it were my mind,
For harmony, set al these babes to school,
And sing such notes, as might in every kind
Disgrace them quite, and make their courage cool.
But should I so? non no will I not.
Let brutish beasts, hear such brute birds as those.
(for like to like, the proverb saith I wot)
And should I then, my cunning skill disclose?
For such unkind, as let the cuckoo fly,
To suck mine eggs, whiles I sit in the thick?
And rather praise, the chattering of a pie,
Than her that sings, with breast against a prick?
Nay let them go, to mark the cuckoo's talk,
The jangling jay, for that becomes them well.
And I the silent night then let them walk,
To heare the Owl, how she doth shreech and yell.
And from henceforth, I will no more constrain
My pleasant voice, to sound, at their request.
But shroud my self, in darksome night and rain,
And learne to couche, full close upon my nest.
Yet if I chance, at any time (percase)
To sing a note, or twain for my disport,
It shall be done, in some such secret place,
That few or none, may therunto resort.
These flatterers, (in love) which falsehood mean,
Not once aproach, to hear my pleasant song.
But such as true, and steadfast lovers been,
Let them come near, for else they do me wrong.
And as I guess, not many miles from hence,
There stands a squire, with pangs of sorrow pressed,
For whom I dare, avowe (in his defence)
He is as true, (in Love) as is the best.

Him will I chear, with chanting all this night:
And with that word, she gan to clear her throat.
Yet never heard I such another note.
It was (thought me) so pleasant and so plain,
Orphæus harp, was never half so sweet,
Tereu, Tereu, and thus she gan to plain,
Most piteously, which made my heart to grieve,

Her second note, was fy, fy, fy, fy, fy,
And that she did, in pleasant wise repeat,
With sweete reports, of heavenly harmony,
But yet it seemd, her gripes of grief were great.
For when she had, so long and taken breath,
Then should you heare, her heavy heart so throb,
As though it had been, overcome with death,
And yet always, in every sigh and sob,
She showed great skill, for tunes of unison,
Her Jug, Jug, Jug, (in grief) had such a grace.
Then stinted she, as if her song were done.
And ere that past, not full a furlong space,
She gan again, in melody to melt,
And many a note, she warbled wondrous well.
Yet can I not (although my heart should swelt)
Remember all, which her sweet tongue did tell.

But one strange note, I noted with the rest
And that said thus: Nêmesis, Nêmesis,
The which me thought, came boldly from her brest,
As though she blamed, (thereby) some thing amiss.

Short tale to make, her singing sounded so,
And pleasd mine ears, with such variety,
That (quite forgetting all the weary woe,
Which I my self felt in my fantasy)
I stood astound, and yet therwith content,
Wishing in heart that (since I might advant,
Of all her speech to know the plain intent,
Which grace herselfe, or else the Gods did grant)
I might therewith, one further favor crave,
To understand, what her sweet notes might mean.
And in that thought, (my whole desire to have)
I fell on sleep, as I on staff did lean.
And in my slumber, had I such a sight,
As yet to think thereon doth glad my mind.
Me thought I saw a darling of delight,
A stately Nymph, a dame of heavenly kind.
Whose glittring gite, so glimpsed in mine eyes,
As (yet) I not, what proper hue it bear,
Ne therewithal, my wits can well devise,
To whom I might her lovely looks compare.
But truth to tell, (for all her smiling cheer)
She cast sometimes, a grievous frowning glance,
As who would say: by this it may appear,
That just revenge, is Pressed for every chance,
In her right hand, (which to and fro did shake)
She bare a scourge, with many a knotty string,
And in her left, a snaffle Bit or brake,
Bebost with gold, and many a jingling ring:
She came apace, and stately did she stay,
And whiles I seemd, amazed very much,
The courteous dame, these words to me did say:
Sir Squire (quoth she) since thy desire is such,
To understand, the notes of Phylomene,
(For so she hight, whom thou calst Nightingale)
And what the sound, of every note might mean,
Give ear a while, and hearken to my tale.

The Gods are good, they hear the hearty prayers,
Of such as crave without a craftie will,
With favour eke, they further such affairs
As tend to good, and mean to do none ill.
And since thy words, were grounded on desire,
Wherby much good, and little harm can grow,
They granted have, the thing thou didst require,
And lovingly, have sent me here below,
To paraphrase, the piteous pleasant notes,
Which Phylomene, doth darkly spend in spring,
For he that well, Dan Nasoes verses notes,
Shall find my words to be no fained thing.
Give ear (sir Squire quith she) and I wil, tell
Both what she was, and how her fortunes fell.

[After this follows the fable of Philomela in a
different verse form, then a conclusion in
iambic pentameter as above]

