it. Still, I think it's fair to claim the publication of Smith's
_Elegaic Sonnets_ (which was enormously popular and went through 11
editions) as the most important moment in spawning the proliferation of
sonnets of the Romantic period. The published output of sonnets in the
18th century was comparatively quite small until the publication of
_Elegaic Sonnets_ in 1784, after which came a very large outpouring of
sonnets from Anna Seward, Cowper, Wordsworth, William Lisle Bowles, Helen
Maria Williams, Ann Radcliffe, Coleridge, Mary Robinson, the Della Cruscans,
and others prior to 1800. Of these, I think only Seward, who published
her sonnets in 1799, had been writing them before 1784.

