My impression is that the legends are spin-offs from myths and
there is something evolving as they're shaped in folk lore oral
and written versions. So the Philomela/Phylomene/Philomel/Procne
myth gets different form through incarnations. I assume the main
broadside influence for Shakespeare was Ovid's Metamorphosis.
By the time T.S. Eliot uses &quot;Tereu&quot; in The Wasteland, we know
enough to associate the plaintive cry the nightengale/Philomel
makes in voicing her fate with symbolizing the whole archetypal
action.

According to one source I find, the Tereus/Procne/Philomela myth
is an example of several Freudean themes: cannibalism,
matricide, fathers unwilling to give up authority over daughters,
and female initiation involving beautiful girl and kingly father,
showing 1) separation between daughter and father, 2) loss of
adolescent identity, and 3) reintegration of identity in ritual.
So, there is maybe some risk involved in the poet identifying
with the nightengale? bookburn

