still not particularly impressed. First, I think you can find analogous
characters prior to Shakespeare in, for instance, Dante and Chaucer and
Ovid. Perhaps it doesn't happen to quite the same extent, but I think
Shakespeare has a certain artificial advantage here in that as a
playwrite, his characters become embodied by actual humans, so that it's
difficult for most of us to know a &quot;pure&quot; textual Hamlet without having
in our minds Scofield or Gielgud or Branagh or Jacobi or Russel Beale or
Burton or Olivier or whatever Hamlets you know.

But I think the primary drawback to Bloom's argument is that modern,
psychologized characters aren't even that common in Shakespeare. Bloom
himself only has a half-dozen or so whom he offers (Hamlet, Falstaff,
Rosiland, Cleopatra, and a few others). The late plays (including some
of my favorites like Cymbaline and Winter's Tale) tend to be more
artificial in some ways, as though the author is retreating to create a
more telescopic amalgamation of human passions and artifice. It's really
bizarre, and to my mind, hugely successful. And even among those few
characters Bloom does think &quot;invent the human,&quot; I'm not sure they're as
internal as Bloom would have us believe. Take that supposedly most
internal of characters, Hamlet, and his supposedly most internal
utterance, the &quot;To be or not to be&quot; soliloquy, for instance. It's termed
entirely in generalities (whithout a single reference to himself or to
anyone else until he turns to Ophelia at the end). Moreover, these dualing
discourses are exactly the sorts found in so many printed books of the
time. We already know Hamlet is a constant reader from his entrance in
Act II scene ii, and Peter Stallybrass has thus described the soliloquy
as more of a hodgepodge (albeit a tour de force hodgepodge) of public
discourse than an internal and personal monologue. The evidence we have
of reception to the play prior to the civil war seems also to encourage a
more &quot;public&quot; reading. In performance, soliloquies seem to have been among
the first things cut, and from diaries, marginalia, commonplace books,
and printed quotations from the text, it seems that people remembered
Hamlet the character less than they remembered, say, the aphorisms of
Polonius. Indeed, the centrality of the internality of Shakespeare's
characters seems to date more from the mid eighteenth century to the turn
of the twentieth, and I think that it's during that period that the &quot;four
great tragedies&quot; become fixed (and fixed around their central characters
- see for instance Bradley's hugely popular 1904 book &quot;Shakespearen Tragedy&quot;
from (which despite its title, centers on only four, or rather on five
characters)). Of the late plays, Cymbaline and the Winter's Tale lose
out to the Tempest, largely, I suspect, because the latter can be
centered around a character who can be identified with the great Author
himself.

